quran[8]{c,v,t,f}:
  10,54,"And if every single self which had committed injustice possessed whatever is in the earth, it would offer it as a ransom. And they hid<a class=""sup""><sup>b </sup></a>their remorse when they saw the punishment, and it was judged between them equitably. And they are not dealt with unjustly.",footnotes:1:Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.
  10,55,"Undoubtedly, to Allah does belong whatever is in the heavens and the earth. Undoubtedly, the promise of Allah is indeed true, but most of them do not know."
  10,56,"He gives life and causes death, and to Him you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a><span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ya’qub read it as: “and to Him you return.”</span>
  10,57,"O mankind, there has come to you an admonition from your Lord and a cure for what lies within the chests and guidance and mercy for the believers."
  10,58,"Say<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>, “In Allah’s grace and in His mercy—in that then, <span class=",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…let them rejoice; it is better than what you<sup>pl</sup> hoard.” hoard.” Roways read it as: “…do rejoice<sup>pl</sup>; it is better than what you hoard.”; it is better than what you hoard.”</span>
  10,59,"Say<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>, “Have you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>seen the provision Allah has sent down for you, some of which you made unlawful and some lawful?” Say<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>, “Did Allah give you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>permission, or do you fabricate lies and attribute them to Allah?”"
  10,60,"And what assumption do those who fabricate lies and attribute them to Allah have about the Day of Resurrection? Most surely, Allah is the Possessor of grace towards mankind, but most of them do not give thanks."
  10,61,"For you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>do not engage in any affair, nor do you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>read any<i class=""s"">(portion) </i>of the Recital{1}, nor do you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>do anything, but We are witnessing over you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>as you undertake it. And not even the weight of an atom in the earth or in the heaven escapes your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord{2}, <span class=",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is <i>Qur’an</i> which literally means ‘recital’ or ‘recitation’.,footnotes:2:A grammatical shift from 1<sup>st</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.,footnotes:3:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Ya’qub and Khalaf read it as: “…escapes your<sup>sg </sup>Lord, nor is there anything smaller or larger but is in an evident record.”Lord, nor is there anything smaller or larger but is in an evident record.”</span>,footnotes:4:Literally ‘scripture’.
